Yeah—elasticity cuts both ways.

It’s what lets you change… and what snaps you back.

⸻

What “elasticity” is in your frame

Think of it like a rubber band between:
	•	Current state (reality)
	•	Desired / imagined state (model)

When they don’t match, you feel tension → emotion.

⸻

Why it feels like a “bitch”

1. Snapback (regression)

You stretch:
	•	new habits
	•	new identity
	•	new standards

Then:
	•	environment
	•	old patterns
	•	biology

…pull you back.

That’s not failure—that’s stored tension releasing

⸻

2. Overstretch (burnout)

If you push too far:
	•	expectations ≫ capacity
	•	identity ≫ behavior

You get:
	•	frustration
	•	shame
	•	collapse

⸻

3. Hidden elasticity (this is the sneaky one)

Even when you “change,” parts of you are still anchored to the old model:
	•	beliefs
	•	environment
	•	feedback loops

So the system self-corrects back.

⸻

The real move isn’t “stretch harder”

It’s:

Change the resting length of the system

⸻

How you actually do that

1. Micro-stretch → lock → repeat

Instead of:
	•	huge change → snapback

Do:
	•	small shift → stabilize → repeat

That rewires the baseline.

⸻

2. Reduce opposing forces

Ask:
	•	what’s pulling me back?

Usually:
	•	environment
	•	identity conflicts
	•	habits

Remove friction instead of just adding force.

⸻

3. Align identity with behavior

If identity says:

“I’m still the old version”

…it will pull you back no matter what.

So you update:

Behavior → evidence → identity → new baseline

⸻

Reframing the pain

That tension you feel?

It’s not punishment—it’s measurement.

It’s literally telling you:
	•	how far you are from alignment
	•	how strong the old attractor still is

⸻

Final compression

Elasticity punishes jumps, but rewards consistent pressure.

And even tighter:

Don’t fight the snapback—reset the baseline so there’s nothing to snap back to.

⸻

You’re basically learning how to redefine your resting state, not just temporarily stretch away from it.

